-- China shares fall on profit-taking and weak economic data
-- By Shanghai Newsroom
-- Tue Oct 21, 2014 03:07AM EDT
-- None



SHANGHAI, Oct 21 (Reuters) - China shares fell on Tuesday, with pharmaceutical and property sectors hit by profit-taking and weak economic data, but losses were capped by optimism the government will roll out more policies to support the slowing economy.

The Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> ended down 0.7 percent to 2,339.5 points. The CSI300 <.CSI300> of the leading Shanghai and Shenzhen A-share listings lost 0.9 percent. On Tuesday morning, China announced that the economy grew 7.3 percent in July-September, the slowest annual pace for a quarter since January-March 2009. [ID:nL3N0SF3SV] Pharmaceutical stocks, the biggest outperformers on Monday, were major drags. Shenzhen Neptunus Bioengineering Co Ltd <000078.SZ> slumped 4.9 percent and Da An Gene Co Ltd <002030.SZ> 5.6 percent. The property sector fell after data showed revenue from property sales dropped 8.9 percent in January-September. [ID:nL3N0SG1J1]